#2.4.1 grammar of graphics: Statistical transformations

#1.What does geom_col() do? How is it different from geom_bar()?
?geom_col()

#geom_col() represents the values of heights of bars in the data, whereas geom_bar() makes the height of the bar proportional to the number of cases in each group. geom_bar() uses stat_count() by default: it counts the number of cases at each x position. geom_col() uses stat_identity(): it leaves the data as is.

#2. Plot ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=hwy)) + geom_bar(). Replace the geom with a stat to make the
#same graph.
ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=hwy)) + geom_bar()

ggplot(data=mpg)+
  stat_count(aes(x=hwy))

 ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + geom_point()

 #this is problem of overplotting where mutiple values are shown for each values of the variable cty #and hwy repsectively. This can be solved by using jitter

 #2. Compare and contrast geom_jitter() with geom_count(). Use vocabulary from the “grammar of graphics” (see section headings) to support your argument.
 
#The geom geom_jitter() adds random variation to the locations points of the graph. In other words, it “jitters” the locations of points slightly. This method reduces overplotting since two points with the same location are unlikely to have the same random variation.
